stories: The presence of musculoskeletal diseases and cognitive disorders in individuals can result in mobility issues and have adverse effects on their mental health. Clinical gait analysis, which is crucial for early detection and treatment, has traditionally depended on costly optical motion capture systems. However, recent advancements in computer vision and deep learning now make more affordable and accessible alternatives possible. This paper presents a new spatio-temporal transformer network to determine essential gait parameters from RGB videos captured by a single-view camera. Evaluations on a public dataset of cerebral palsy patients suggest that this method outperforms existing state-of-the-art approaches, showing significant enhancements in predicting general gait parameters such as walking speed, gait deviation index (GDI), and knee flexion angle at maximum extension. Additionally, it uses fewer parameters and eliminates the need for manual feature extraction.

Musculoskeletal diseases and cognitive disorders in people can cause mobility problems and negatively impact their mental health. Early detection and treatment of these issues have typically relied on expensive optical motion capture systems for clinical gait analysis. However, new developments in computer vision and deep learning enable more affordable and accessible options. This paper introduces a novel spatio-temporal transformer network that can extract critical gait parameters from RGB videos taken with a single-view camera. The method has been tested on a public dataset of cerebral palsy patients and outperforms existing state-of-the-art approaches in predicting general gait parameters, such as walking speed, gait deviation index (GDI), and knee flexion angle at maximum extension. Furthermore, it uses fewer parameters and does not require manual feature extraction.

Musculoskeletal and cognitive conditions in individuals can lead to issues with mobility and have adverse effects on their mental health. The approach has been evaluated on a public dataset of cerebral palsy patients and has shown better performance than existing state-of-the-art methods in estimating general gait parameters, including walking speed, gait deviation index (GDI), and knee flexion angle at maximum extension. Moreover, it utilizes fewer parameters and does not necessitate manual feature extraction.

A newly published article presents a spatio-temporal transformer network that can extract crucial gait parameters from single-view RGB videos obtained by a camera. This model, tested on a free cerebral palsy video dataset, showed improved precision in measuring extensive gait metrics, like walking speed, gait deviation index (GDI), and maximum knee flexion angle, surpassing previous techniques. Additionally, this model functions with fewer parameters and doesn't need manual feature extraction.

Muscle strength, bone health, and mental well-being challenges can lead to decreased mobility. In the past, costly optical motion capture systems were typically utilized in clinical environments to evaluate gait abnormalities. A recent article introduces a spatio-temporal transformer network capable of extracting vital gait parameters from single-view RGB videos captured by a camera. This model, examined on a free cerebral palsy video dataset, demonstrated enhanced accuracy in determining extensive gait measurements, such as walking speed, gait deviation index (GDI), and maximum knee flexion angle, outperforming prior methods. Furthermore, this model operates with fewer parameters and doesn't rely on manual feature extraction.
